Slide 6 — Tip Motion Pipeline

“Now that we have the cable modeled, the next challenge is actually controlling the tip — making it go exactly where we want, smoothly and precisely.

The pipeline starts with a user command. You give it two angles — pitch and yaw — basically telling the tip ‘go 15 degrees to the right’ or ‘10 degrees up.’ Think of it as the digital equivalent of pushing the joystick on the real borescope.

But here’s the thing — we have 50 joints in that chain, and we can’t just rotate the last one and call it a day. We need the entire cable to curve naturally, like a real flexible probe would. That’s where SLERP interpolation comes in — Spherical Linear Interpolation. It takes that single command and distributes it across all 50 joints in a smooth curve, where joints near the tip rotate more and joints near the base barely move. The result looks organic — exactly how a real cable bends.

Once each joint knows its target angle, we use something called a DriveAPI — this is what actually tells the physics engine to move each joint to its position. Each drive has stiffness, which controls how firmly it holds the target, and damping, which prevents it from snapping or overshooting. Getting those values right is what makes the difference between motion that looks robotic and motion that looks natural.

And then PhysX — NVIDIA’s physics engine — simulates everything in real time. What you’re seeing in the video is the result: one command in, smooth controlled tip motion out.”

